│ stop({"edit_points": [[2499, 2511,                                       │
│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/GVN.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1. Understanding    │
│ the Issue:\nThe reproducer triggers a crash in the verifier after        │
│ running GVN because GVN replaces the pointer operand of                  │
│ llvm.lifetime.start/end with null, based on information derived from an  │
│ llvm.assume that equates an alloca pointer with null. The verifier       │
│ correctly asserts that llvm.lifetime.start/end can only be used on an    │
│ alloca or poison, not on null.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe opt log   │
│ shows alias/modref info and then the verifier error complaining about    │
│ lifetime intrinsics being applied to null after GVN. From reading        │
│ GVN.cpp, the first relevant transformation is the in-block equality      │
│ replacement driven by ReplaceOperandsWithMap. In processAssume (around   │
│ 2161 onward), GVN sets up ReplaceOperandsWithMap entries to canonicalize │
│ operands based on equalities observed from assume, including mapping one │
│ side of an equivalence comparison to the other (e.g.,                    │
│ ReplaceOperandsWithMap[CmpLHS] = CmpRHS). For icmp eq between %alloca    │
│ and null, the heuristic can map %alloca -> null. Later,                  │
│ replaceOperandsForInBlockEquality walks instructions and applies this    │
│ map, which affects llvm.lifetime.start/end operands.\n\n3. Root Cause    │
│ Analysis:\nIn replaceOperandsForInBlockEquality, GVN blindly substitutes │
│ operands of any instruction with mapped values without checking          │
│ instruction-specific constraints. This is unsafe for lifetime intrinsics │
│ which have strict operand rules: their pointer operand must be an alloca │
│ or poison. Thus, substituting an alloca with null for lifetime.start/end │
│ breaks IR invariants and leads to the verifier error. Other parts of GVN │
