  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe reproducer triggers a
crash in the verifier after running GVN because GVN replaces the pointer
operand of llvm.lifetime.start/end with null, based on information derived
from an llvm.assume that equates an alloca pointer with null. The verifier
correctly asserts that llvm.lifetime.start/end can only be used on an alloca
or poison, not on null.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe opt log shows
alias/modref info and then the verifier error complaining about lifetime
intrinsics being applied to null after GVN. From reading GVN.cpp, the first
relevant transformation is the in-block equality replacement driven by
ReplaceOperandsWithMap. In processAssume (around 2161 onward), GVN sets up
ReplaceOperandsWithMap entries to canonicalize operands based on equalities
observed from assume, including mapping one side of an equivalence
comparison to the other (e.g., ReplaceOperandsWithMap[CmpLHS] = CmpRHS). For
icmp eq between %alloca and null, the heuristic can map %alloca -> null.
Later, replaceOperandsForInBlockEquality walks instructions and applies this
map, which affects llvm.lifetime.start/end operands.\n\n3. Root Cause
Analysis:\nIn replaceOperandsForInBlockEquality, GVN blindly substitutes
operands of any instruction with mapped values without checking
instruction-specific constraints. This is unsafe for lifetime intrinsics
which have strict operand rules: their pointer operand must be an alloca or
poison. Thus, substituting an alloca with null for lifetime.start/end breaks
IR invariants and leads to the verifier error. Other parts of GVN (e.g.,
propagateEquality/replacement via replaceDominatedUsesWithIf) consult
canReplacePointersInUseIfEqual to avoid illegal pointer replacements, but
the in-block equality fast path does not.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nWe
should guard replaceOperandsForInBlockEquality to skip replacements for
llvm.lifetime.start/end entirely (conservative and safe), or at least avoid
replacing their pointer operands. A minimal and robust fix is to
early-return false when encountering these intrinsics to avoid any operand
rewrite.\n\nEdit at llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/GVN.cpp, function
replaceOperandsForInBlockEquality:\n- Add a check at the beginning of the
function to detect IntrinsicInst with Intrinsic::lifetime_start or
Intrinsic::lifetime_end and immediately return false. This prevents illegal
substitution of their operands via ReplaceOperandsWithMap.\n\nConcrete
change (lines 2499-2511):\nReplace the function body start with:\n\nbool
GVNPass::replaceOperandsForInBlockEquality(Instruction *Instr) const {\n  //
Do not replace operands of lifetime intrinsics. Their pointer operand must\n
// remain an alloca or poison; substituting via equality can break IR
invariants.\n  if (auto *II = dyn_cast<IntrinsicInst>(Instr)) {\n    switch
(II->getIntrinsicID()) {\n    case Intrinsic::lifetime_start:\n    case
Intrinsic::lifetime_end:\n      return false;\n    default:\n      break;\n
}\n  }\n  bool Changed = false;\n  for (unsigned OpNum = 0; OpNum <
Instr->getNumOperands(); ++OpNum) {\n    Value *Operand =
Instr->getOperand(OpNum);\n    auto It =
ReplaceOperandsWithMap.find(Operand);\n    if (It !=
ReplaceOperandsWithMap.end()) {\n      LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << \"GVN replacing:
\" << *Operand << \" with \"\n                        << *It->second << \"
in instruction \" << *Instr << '\\n');\n      Instr->setOperand(OpNum,
It->second);\n      Changed = true;\n    }\n  }\n  return
Changed;\n}\n\nThis preserves the existing behavior for other instructions
while avoiding the invalid replacement for lifetime intrinsics.\n\n5.
Conclusion:\nThe crash is caused by GVN's in-block equality replacement
substituting an alloca with null in llvm.lifetime.start/end, violating
verifier constraints. By skipping operand replacement for lifetime
intrinsics in replaceOperandsForInBlockEquality, we maintain IR correctness
and prevent the verifier assertion. This fix is conservative and aligns with
the stricter checks used in other GVN replacement paths (which consult
canReplacePointersInUseIfEqual).",
